<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>Dictionaries are one of the fundamental data types that we use in Python to solve real problems. These are handy when we donâ€™t need a sequential list of items, and it is more useful to have unique identifiers for looking up values. Being able to manipulate dictionaries and access items is necessary for effective programming. In this hands-on lab, weâ€™ll be working through some exercises demonstrating that we understand how to add, remove, modify, and read items from dictionaries in Python. Weâ€™ll be asked to perform actions on a dictionary to meet some checkpoint requirements provided to us within a Python file.</p>

<p>To feel comfortable completing this lab youâ€™ll want to know how to do the following:</p>

<p>Working with dictionary literals. Watch the â€œDictionariesâ€ video from the Certified Entry-Level Python Programmer Certification course.
Using Dictionary functions and methods. Watch the â€œDictionary Methodsâ€ video from the Certified Entry-Level Python Programmer Certification course.</p>

<h2 id="the-scenario">The Scenario</h2>

<p>From within the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">using-dictionaries.py</code> file, weâ€™ll be modifying the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">users</code> list so that the assertions throughout the file all succeed eventually. As weâ€™re working through the tasks we can run the file. Whenever Python gets to a line that starts with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">assert</code>, it will raise an error and stop executing if we havenâ€™t met the criteria. The first error will look like this:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$ python3.7 using-dictionaries.py
